### Finding $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2^{\large -}}f(x)$

For $x$-values smaller than $2$, the appropriate rule for $f(x)$ is $\ln(x)$.

Since $\ln(x)$ is continuous for $0<x<2$, any limit in this interval is equal to the expression's value at that limit:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2^{\large -}}f(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2^{\large -}}[\ln(x)]\qquad\gray{\ln(x)\text{ is the rule for }x<2}
\\\\
&=\ln(2)\qquad\gray{\ln(x)\text{ is continuous at }x=2}
\end{align}$

### Finding $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1^{\large -}}g(x)$

For $x$-values smaller than $-1$, the appropriate rule for $g(x)$ is $e^x$.

Since $e^x$ is **continuous** for all real numbers, any limit is equal to the expression's value at that limit:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1^{\large -}}g(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -1^{\large -}}[e^x]\qquad\gray{e^x\text{ is the rule for }x<-1}
\\\\
&=e^{-1}\qquad\gray{e^x\text{ is continuous at }x=-1}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{e}
\end{align}$

### Finding $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0^{\large +}}h(x)$

For $x$-values larger than $0$, the appropriate rule for $h(x)$ is $\sqrt{x+\pi}$.

Since $\sqrt{x+\pi}$ is **continuous** for $x\geq0$, any limit in this interval is equal to the expression's value at that limit:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0^{\large +}}h(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0^{\large +}}[\sqrt{x+\pi}]\qquad\gray{\sqrt{x+\pi}\text{ is the rule for }x>0}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{0+\pi}\qquad\gray{\sqrt{x+\pi}\text{ is continuous at }x=0}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{\pi}
\end{align}$

### Finding $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1^{\large +}}h(x)$

For $x$-values larger than $1$, the appropriate rule for $h(x)$ is $\sqrt{2x}$.

Since $\sqrt{2x}$ is **continuous** for $x\geq1$, any limit in this interval is equal to the expression's value at that limit:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1^{\large +}}h(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 1^{\large +}}[\sqrt{2x}]\qquad\gray{\sqrt{2x}\text{ is the rule for }x>1}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{2(1)}\qquad\gray{\sqrt{2x}\text{ is continuous at }x=1}
\\\\
&=\sqrt{2}
\end{align}$

### Finding $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^{\large +}}g(x)$

For $x$-values larger than $-2$, the appropriate rule for $g(x)$ is $-\small\dfrac{\cos(x+2)}{2}$.

Since $-\small\dfrac{\cos(x+2)}{2}$ is **continuous** for all real numbers, any limit is equal to the expression's value at that limit:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^{\large +}}g(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^{\large +}}-\dfrac{\cos(x+2)}{2}\qquad\gray{-\dfrac{\cos(x+2)}{2}\text{ is the rule for }x>-2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{\cos(-2+2)}{2}\qquad\gray{-\dfrac{\cos(x+2)}{2}\text{ is continuous at }x=-2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{1}{2}
\end{align}$

### Finding $\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^{\large -}}g(x)$

For $x$-values smaller than $-2$, the appropriate rule for $g(x)$ is $\dfrac{1}{x}$.

Since $\dfrac{1}{x}$ is continuous for $x\leq -2$, any limit in this interval is equal to the expression's value at that limit:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^{\large -}}g(x)
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to -2^{\large -}}\dfrac{1}{x}\qquad\gray{\dfrac{1}{x}\text{ is the rule for }x<-2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{1}{-2}\qquad\gray{\dfrac{1}{x}\text{ is continuous at }x=-2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{1}{2}
\end{align}$
